== Roasted Veggies ==

Adjust racks to top and middle positions and preheat #oven{} to 425 degrees. Wash
and dry produce. Place @butter{4%tbsp} in #freezer{}.

> TIP: Don't cut the butter into pieces! Keeping it whole will make it easier to
> grate in Step 3.

Trim, peel, and cut @carrots{12%ounce}(trimmed and peeled) into sticks (like
fries; ours were 3 inches long and 1/3 inch thick). Halve, peel, and cut
@red onion{1}(peeled and cut into 1-inch-thick wedges).

Toss carrots and onion on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @cooking oil{drizzle},
@salt{} and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack until veggies are tender and lightly
browned, ~{20-25%minutes}. Remove from oven; reduce oven temperature to 375
degrees (you'll bake the scones at this temperature in Step 5).

Meanwhile, trim and thinly slice @mini cucumber{1}(trimmed and sliced) into
rounds. Quarter @lemon{1}(quartered). Finely chop @chives{1/4%ounce}(finely chopped).
Pick and finely chop fronds from @dill{1/4%ounce}(finely chopped).

In a #small bowl{}, combine cucumber, juice from half the lemon, a pinch of
chives, a pinch of dill, and @salt{}. Transfer to the refrigerator to pickle.

== Scone Dough ==

In a #large bowl{}, combine @flour{1%cup}, @cheddar cheese{1%cup}(shredded),
@baking powder{1.5%tsp}, @garlic powder{1%tsp}, remaining chives, remaining dill,
@sugar{1/2%tsp}, and @salt{1/2%tsp}. Stir to thoroughly combine.

> No grater? No problem! Finely dice your butter into large pea-size pieces, then
> transfer back to the freezer to chill for another 5-10 minutes before adding to
> the flour mixture.

Remove butter from freezer and grate on the largest holes of a #box grater{}
directly over bowl with flour mixture.

Using a #spoon{}, gently toss until butter is evenly coated in flour mixture.

== Assembly ==

In a second small bowl, whisk together @sour cream{1.5%tbsp}, 1/4 cup + 1 tbsp
water, and juice from one lemon wedge. Add sour cream mixture to bowl with flour
mixture.

Using a large spoon, stir until just incorporated, 8-10 times.

> TIP: Don't worry if your dough is crumbly—it should be shaggy and a bit lumpy.

Transfer dough to a clean work surface. Using your hands, shape into a 3-inch
disk; wrap in #plastic wrap{} and transfer to the freezer for ~{15%minutes}.

Once dough has chilled for 15 minutes, unwrap and transfer dough to a clean work
surface. Using your hands, shape into a 5-inch disk (two 5-inch disks for 4
servings); cut into four equal wedges (you'll have eight wedges for 4).

Transfer scones to a second parchment-lined baking sheet, spacing them at least
2 inches apart. Bake on middle rack (be sure oven temperature has reduced to
375 degrees first!) until bottoms are golden brown and tops are lightly browned,
~{20-25%minutes}. Remove from oven and let cool ~{5%minutes}.

== Dijonnaise and Bacon ==

While scones cool, in a third small bowl, combine @mayonnaise{2%tbsp} and
@dijon mustard{2%tsp}.

Heat a #medium dry pan{} over medium-high heat. Add @bacon{4%ounce}; cook,
turning occasionally and adjusting heat if browning too quickly, until crispy,
~{6-10%minutes}. Turn off heat; transfer to a #paper-towel-lined plate{}.

> Fill scones with bacon along with roasted veggies and quickles (draining first).

== Assembly and Serving ==

Halve scones horizontally.

Spread cut sides of scones with Dijonnaise. Fill scones with roasted veggies and
as many @quickles{} (draining first) as you like. Divide sandos between plates;
serve with any remaining quickles on the side.

> Bacon is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.